SIMPLE: scamble
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scamble
<hw>Scam"ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Scambled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Scambling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. OD.
<ets>schampelen</ets> to deviate, to slip, <ets>schampen</ets> to go
away, escape, slip, and E. <ets>scamper</ets>,
<ets>shamble</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To move awkwardly; to be
shuffling, irregular, or unsteady; to sprawl; to shamble.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Some <xex>scambling</xex> shifts.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Dr. H. More.</au>
⟦ldquo⟧A fine old hall, but a <xex>scambling</xex> house.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Evelyn.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To move about pushing and jostling; to be rude and
turbulent; to scramble.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>scambling</xex> and
unquiet time did push it out of . . . question.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scamble</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Scamble
<hw>Scam"ble</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To mangle.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Mortimer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scambler</ent>⟦br⟧
